05531nam a22007215i 9780823291250DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20222013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232912507 a10.1515/97808232912502doi  a(DE-B1597)566068  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0360502bisacsh00aConstitutionalism in the Approach and Aftermath of the Civil War /ced. by Paul D. Moreno, Johnathan O'Neill. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b9 Illustrations, black and white  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe North's Civil War00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPrologue: A Second American Revolution? George Washington and the Origins of the Civil War -- tPart I Constitutionalism Endangered: The Road to Civil War -- t1 Martin Van Buren as Statesman: State Rights and the Rise of the “Free Soil” Party -- t2 Lincoln on Black Citizenship -- t3 Lincoln, Secession, and Revolution: Th e Civil War Challenge to the Founding -- tPart II Legal Change and Constitutional Politics in Reconstruction and the Gilded Age -- t4 The Trial of Jefferson Davis and the Americanization of Treason Law -- t5 At Every Fireside: Constitutional Politics in the Era of Reconstruction -- t6 “The Legitimate Object of Government”: Constitutional Problems of Civil War–Era Republican Policy -- tPart III Contesting the Legacy of Lincoln and the Civil War in the Progressive Era -- tWoodrow Wilson and the Meaning of the Lincoln Legacy -- t8 The Idea of Constitutional Conservatism in the Early Twentieth Century -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe irreducibly constitutional nature of the Civil War’s prelude and legacy is the focus of this absorbing collection of nine essays by a diversity of political theorists and historians. The contributors examine key constitutional developments leading up to the war, the crucial role of Abraham Lincoln’s statesmanship, and how the constitutional aspects of the war and Reconstruction endured in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. This thoughtful, informative volume covers a wide range of topics: from George Washington’s conception of the Union and his fears for its future to Martin Van Buren’s state-centered, anti-secessionist federalism; from Lincoln’s approach to citizenship for African Americans to Woodrow Wilson’s attempt to appropriate Lincoln for the goals of Progressivism. Each essay zeroes in on the constitutional causes or consequences of the war and emphasizes how constitutional principles shape political activity. Accordingly, important figures, disputes, and judicial decisions are placed within the broader context of the constitutional system to explain how ideas and institutions, independently and in dialogue with the courts, have oriented political action and shaped events over time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aHISTORY / United States / Civil War Period (1850-1877).2bisacsh1 aBelz, Herman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenedict, Michael Les, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsh, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFornieri, Joseph R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoreno, Paul D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoreno, Paul D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMorrison, Jeffry H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO'Neill, Johnathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aO’Neill, Johnathan, e